            <biogHist>
                <p>Isabella Ross was born to Ronald (Ranald) MacDonald, a farmer, and Mary MacDonald
                    née Currie. The earliest recorded details are from the 1841 Census where
                    Isabella (50) is living with her husband Hugh (or Ewan) with her children Donald
                    (40) and Mary (40), together with their three year old nephew Rory MacDonald, in
                    Upper Bornish, South Uist. Her son and husband are farm labourers. Ten years
                    later, her husband was deceased and she and her son were classed as paupers.
                    Staying with them in Upper Bornish was Catherine MacMillan, aged 70, also a
                    pauper. By 1861 she and her son were living with Alexander Morrison and his
                    family in Sniseabhal to the north of Upper Bornish. </p>
                <p>In 1865 Isabella died at Morrison’s house of natural causes at the age of 112
                    and an Archibald Morrison signed the death certificate.</p>
                <p>Carmichael records that she died with 'all her faculties'. Her son, Donald, died
                    the following year on 10 July 1866, at Stoneybridge, suffering from a long-term
                    ‘disease of the brain’ and apoplexy [Note: his father's name is recorded as
                    Ewan]. Margaret Morrison signed the certificate.</p>
